I've been watching food television on PBS and other networks for decades. I'm an avid home cook. The French phrase was one of the easier clues for me to solve. Our experience, expertise, interests and locations vary widely. 
Yes, I agree that mize en place is a fairly specialized term. It's chef talk and it's French. In most commercial kitchens they call it a "prep station." It's not common English regardless of who has and will comment here says it is. For a Tuesday especially, it probably should have been clued a little easier.

@John

But, how could you clue that any easier?

I didn't know the phrase (got it from crosses) but now that I know, the clue as written seems about as easy/straightforward as possible.

@John

MISE EN PLACE is not a prep station. It’s the act of getting all your ingredients ready before you start cooking so you’re not scouring your fridge for that shredded cheese while the eggs are burning in their pan. 

If you know the term, it’s a gimme. If you don’t, it’s word salad. It was a no-brainer for me, and I’m neither a gourmet chef nor a watcher of pretentious cooking shows.

@Bill in Yokohama
The New York Times article describing how to solve a crossword clearly states foreign language answers will be hinted in clue. This is widely ignored by constructors and editors. Defenders of the Crossword will point out that 100% of the time, the issue is the solver's. The foreign word or phrase is actually in common use by English speakers.
Read the comments here and you'll see it would have helped those unfamiliar with mise en place to be told it was at least not English. I think that's a reasonable complaint on a Tuesday.

@John

Regardless of how the clue is worded, every definition I have looked at agrees with my prior knowledge that MISE EN PLACE refers to the process of gathering up everything needed for a recipe or a night’s service at a restaurant, not the prep station where it’s done. 

People in the restaurant business may refer to the prep station that way, but I imagine only snooty chefs do (at least in Anglophone countries).

