@Grant, mise-en-place is a very specific prep. If you're working the grill, for example, your mise might include the spice rubs and sauce ingredients you need for YOUR particular station. 

Prep is getting things ready that everyone in the kitchen uses: chopping onions, garlic, and herbs; peeling and slicing/dicing veggies; making stock, etc.

Of course, in an average small restaurant or a chain, the traditional French terminology is less likely to be used. But it's definitely used in classical and/or fancier establishments.

